description:
The current code has already fixed part of the original regression, so this issue is now narrower than its title suggests. Interrupted staged-build manifests are already written with `workspace_path_hash` derived from the indexed target path, and manifest-based resume candidate selection already prefers `index_target_path` over caller cwd when deciding compatibility. That means explicit resume and orphaned-build discovery can already tolerate older manifests whose workspace hash was captured from the wrong cwd, as long as the stored `index_target_path` still matches the requested target.

The remaining bug is the broader resume-identity contract outside that manifest path. The generic resume fingerprint metadata used by `status --json`, `search --json`, and last-success marker persistence is still derived from `os.getcwd()` rather than the indexed repo path. As a result, the same cache can report different last-success resume identities depending only on which launcher or caller cwd invoked the command, even when the indexed target, cache contents, schema, and embedding profile are unchanged.

Observed current state as of 2026-03-26:
- interrupted staged-build manifest writing and manifest compatibility checks are already target-path-aware;
- top-level resume fingerprint generation and last-success persistence are still caller-cwd-aware;
- the bootstrap wrapper `scripts/gloggur` masks part of the problem because it `cd`s to the repo root by default, while the plain console entrypoint `.venv/bin/gloggur` preserves caller cwd;
- a plain console-script probe still produces a false `last_success_resume_fingerprint_match = false` when only the caller cwd changes, even though `needs_reindex = false` and `resume_decision = "resume_ok"` remain unchanged.

This issue should therefore normalize resume identity end-to-end around the indexed target path (or another canonical target-derived identity), not just staged manifest compatibility.

The original F8 backlog text no longer matches the current product surface. The repo still contains a small legacy evidence/grounding helper module (`src/gloggur/search/evidence.py`) that can normalize retrieval results into evidence items and score them with `min_confident_evidence_v1`, but that functionality is not part of the supported public `search --json` / `find --json` contract anymore.

Today, the pre-ContextPack evidence flags are intentionally treated as removed. `--with-evidence-trace`, `--validate-grounding`, and `--fail-on-ungrounded` are still accepted as hidden compatibility flags, but `_execute_search_command(...)` immediately fails closed with `error.code = search_contract_v1_removed` when any of them are used. Public docs now tell agent integrators to branch on ContextPack v2 fields such as `summary.strategy`, `summary.reason`, `summary.next_action`, and hit count instead of expecting a dedicated evidence trace or validator payload.

Observed current state as of 2026-03-26:
- the evidence helper functions exist and are still unit-tested in isolation;
- the public search/find CLI contract no longer emits `evidence_trace` or validation blocks;
- default search metadata explicitly reports `grounding_validation_enabled = false` and `grounding_validation_passed = null`;
- docs and migration notes frame the old evidence/grounding flags as removed v1 behavior rather than a current feature.

This issue is therefore not “add evidence trace hooks from scratch”. It is now a reconciliation task: either promote evidence/grounding back into a supported ContextPack v2 contract with a clearly defined schema, or retire/remove the leftover legacy plumbing so the codebase, docs, and backlog all agree that summary-based grounding is the supported path.

Current code makes notebook support a format-modeling problem, not a simple extension-registration task. `.ipynb` is absent from the default extension map and language support contract, `ParserRegistry().get_parser_for_path("sample.ipynb")` returns `None`, `is_indexable_source_path("sample.ipynb", ...)` returns `False`, and adding `.ipynb` to `supported_extensions` currently fails extension-policy validation because there is no parser mapping. More importantly, the indexing pipeline assumes one UTF-8 source buffer per file, contiguous line/byte spans in that raw file, parser-emitted symbols tied directly to those raw lines, and graph/reference extraction over code-like source text. Notebook support therefore needs an explicit document model and safety policy before any implementation should begin.

This issue should research and pin the current feasibility questions in terms of the existing architecture:
- how notebook JSON should be normalized into retrieval/index units (whole-file JSON, per-cell virtual files, or a hybrid document model);
- whether code cells, markdown cells, outputs, attachments, and notebook-level metadata are indexed at all;
- what sanitization/redaction policy is required for outputs and metadata, including large embedded data, HTML output, tracebacks, execution counts, and potentially sensitive values in saved results;
- how virtual notebook cells map back to stable file/line/byte spans given that current models assume one contiguous source buffer per file;
- whether symbol extraction/graph edges should exist only for code cells in supported languages, and how those symbols relate back to the notebook path;
- what a staged rollout looks like if the repo only wants notebook retrieval first and notebook symbol/graph support later.

Observed current state as of 2026-03-26:
- `.ipynb` is not part of `GloggurConfig.supported_extensions`, not part of `ParserRegistry`'s extension map, and not present in the published language support contract.
- Indexing and inspect flows are designed to skip unsupported extensions or fail with parser-unavailable contracts, not to parse structured container formats and fan out into nested language fragments.
- Core models (`Symbol`, `SymbolChunk`, `EdgeRecord`) and `LineByteSpanIndex` assume stable file-level line/byte ranges in the original file content, which is an awkward fit for notebook cells rendered from JSON arrays.
- Graph extraction is currently import/call/reference oriented for code languages; there is no model yet for markdown links, notebook cell dependencies, execution order, or output-derived references.
- There is no existing notebook guidance, fixtures, or tests anywhere in the repo, so the first deliverable needs to be an explicit recommendation and follow-up plan rather than ad hoc implementation.

design:
Research touchpoints in the current codebase:
- `src/gloggur/config.py`, `src/gloggur/parsers/registry.py`, and `src/gloggur/parsers/support_contract.py`: document the current extension-policy and support-contract barriers. Any notebook plan must decide whether `.ipynb` becomes a first-class supported extension, a parser-extension override, or a special pre-parser ingestion path.
- `src/gloggur/indexer/indexer.py` and `src/gloggur/cli/main.py`: both indexing and inspect currently operate on one decoded UTF-8 text blob per file and assume a parser can run directly on that blob. Research should state whether notebook ingestion happens before parser selection and whether unsupported-extension diagnostics need a dedicated notebook mode.
- `src/gloggur/byte_spans.py` and `src/gloggur/models.py`: current spans/chunks/edges are anchored to contiguous file lines and bytes. Research must propose how notebook cells map to these fields or whether notebooks require virtual path/span metadata extensions.
- `src/gloggur/graph/extractor.py` and `src/gloggur/symbol_index/indexer.py`: current graph/reference extraction is code-token and import/call based. Research should decide whether notebook support initially excludes graph/reference extraction, scopes it to code cells only, or introduces new notebook-specific edge types.

Questions the research deliverable should answer explicitly:
- ingestion model: raw notebook JSON vs flattened virtual documents vs per-cell synthetic files;
- safety model: whether outputs/attachments/metadata are excluded by default, size-limited, redacted, or optionally indexed behind an explicit flag;
- retrieval model: whether markdown cells should be searchable as documentation-like text, whether code cells should participate in symbol search, and whether outputs should ever reach embeddings;
- path/span model: how search/inspect results point back to a cell and line in the original notebook file;
- rollout model: minimum safe slice versus later richer notebook semantics.

Non-goal:
- Do not implement notebook parsing in this issue. The intended outcome is a concrete recommendation, architectural boundaries, and follow-up implementation tasks grounded in this repo's current contracts.

description:
Current code does not support HTML or CSS today, but unlike notebook support this is not fundamentally blocked by the file/span model. `.html` and `.css` are absent from the default extension map and published language support contract, `ParserRegistry().get_parser_for_path(...)` returns `None` for both, and adding them to `supported_extensions` currently fails extension-policy validation because there is no parser mapping. At the same time, the installed `tree_sitter_language_pack` already provides raw parsers for both languages, and the repo's existing line/byte/span/chunk models already fit plain-text markup/stylesheets. The missing work is therefore not “can the repo read these files at all”, but rather which parser adapter shape, symbol model, chunking strategy, and graph semantics are worth standardizing.

This issue should be treated as an architectural research task for first-class HTML/CSS support under the current codebase constraints:
- decide whether HTML and CSS should ship together or as separate phases;
- decide whether the first deliverable is retrieval-only, CSS symbol extraction first, or limited HTML symbol extraction rather than a broad “everything in markup is a symbol” approach;
- define what counts as a symbol in each language (for example CSS selector groups, custom properties, keyframes/media rules, HTML ids/custom elements/templates/script-style blocks, or no HTML symbols in phase 1);
- define whether style/script blocks embedded in HTML are indexed as plain markup text, extracted as nested language fragments, or ignored initially;
- define whether graph/reference semantics are in scope at all, especially any HTML↔CSS linkage such as class/id usage, or whether graph support should wait until after basic retrieval/indexing is stable.

Observed current state as of 2026-03-26:
- `.html` and `.css` are explicitly outside the default support contract and parser registry today.
- Raw tree-sitter grammars for both languages are already available in the installed dependency set, but `TreeSitterParser` hard-fails because `_LANGUAGE_SPECS` only covers the current code languages.
- Existing models already assume one plain-text file with contiguous line/byte spans, which is compatible with HTML/CSS as files; the hard part is choosing useful symbol and graph semantics instead of forcing them into the current function/class/method mental model.
- Search/index/inspect flows currently skip these extensions by policy, but query parsing already treats `.html` and `.css` as plausible path-like suffixes, which suggests users may already ask about these files even though they are not indexed structurally.
- There is no existing HTML/CSS guidance, fixtures, or parser-capability corpus in the repo, so the first deliverable should be a clear recommendation and scoped follow-up plan rather than speculative implementation.
